*Formula 1: Drive to Survive* is a [British](/British_people) [television documentary](/Television_documentary) series that, for better or worse, has undeniably reshaped the public perception of elite motorsport. Produced through a collaboration between the streaming giant [Netflix](/Netflix) and the [Formula One Group](/Formula_One_Group) itself, the series aims to pull back the curtain, offering viewers a supposedly "behind-the-scenes" glimpse into the intricate lives of the drivers, the high-stakes strategies of the teams, and the dramatic narratives unfolding across the [Formula One World Championship](/Formula_One_World_Championship) each year.

Since its debut in 2019, the series has consistently delivered one season annually, providing a deep dive into the preceding year's championship. A grand total of seven seasons have been released to date, with [the latest installment](/Formula_1:_Drive_to_Survive_season_7) having premiered on 7 March 2025. This series also famously participated in a rather peculiar [crossover event](/The_Netflix_Cup) with the golf-focused [Full Swing](/Full_Swing_(2023_TV_series)) on [Netflix](/Netflix) in November 2023, aptly named [The Netflix Cup](/The_Netflix_Cup), further cementing its place in the streaming service's sports docu-series stable.

### Production and Concept

The genesis of *Formula 1: Drive to Survive* was officially announced on 24 March 2018. [Formula One](/Formula_One_Group) confirmed that [Netflix](/Netflix) had commissioned an initial ten-episode [docudrama](/Docudrama) series, promising an unprecedented and exclusive behind-the-scenes perspective on the [2018 Formula One World Championship](/2018_Formula_One_World_Championship). This marked a significant shift in [Formula One's](/Formula_One_Group) approach to media, opening up what was once a notoriously closed-off paddock to a broader audience. The initial reception must have been sufficient, as on 24 July 2019, [Formula One](/Formula_One_Group) announced the renewal of the series for a second season, which would cover the [2019 Formula One World Championship](/2019_Formula_One_World_Championship). This subsequent season notably involved all ten teams on the grid, a crucial expansion from the first season which had some notable absences.

The creative force behind the series hails from Box to Box Films, with [James Gay-Rees](/James_Gay-Rees) and Paul Martin serving as the executive producers, the architects of this particular brand of high-octane narrative. Sophie Todd is credited as the production's showrunner, guiding the overall vision and storytelling.

Interestingly, [James Gay-Rees](/James_Gay-Rees) later revealed on The Fast Lane Podcast that the concept for *Drive to Survive* wasn't always the all-encompassing, grid-wide spectacle it became. Initially, the idea was far more contained, conceived as a series exclusively centered around the inner workings of [Red Bull Racing](/Red_Bull_Racing). One can only imagine the sheer volume of *Red Bull* branding that would have entailed. Fortunately, or perhaps inevitably, the concept broadened, evolving into the comprehensive F1 series we now know.

The production schedule for the 2020 season encountered an unavoidable, globally inconvenient hurdle: filming, which commenced in March, had to be abruptly suspended until July due to the pervasive [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic). This unprecedented interruption undoubtedly added another layer of real-world drama to an already dramatic sport, even if the series itself tends to manufacture its own.

### Experts

The series features a rotating cast of commentators and analysts, providing context and, occasionally, manufactured tension, to the unfolding events.

*   [Will Buxton](/Will_Buxton)
*   [Jennie Gow](/Jennie_Gow) (seasons 3-4)
*   [Danica Patrick](/Danica_Patrick) (season 6)
*   [Claire Williams](/Claire_Williams) (season 7)

### Episodes

Each season of *Formula 1: Drive to Survive* consists of ten episodes, each meticulously crafted (or, depending on your perspective, heavily edited) to present a coherent narrative arc across the [Formula One World Championship](/Formula_One_World_Championship) calendar. The release schedule has been remarkably consistent, typically arriving in late February or early March, just before the start of the next racing season, ensuring that the audience is primed for more high-speed drama.

