### Spin-offs

The undeniable, if somewhat manufactured, success of *Drive to Survive* created a blueprint that other motorsports were quick to emulate. In 2020, a series with a strikingly similar format was launched on [F1 TV](/F1_TV), focusing on the feeder series to [Formula One](/Formula_One_Group). This spin-off, titled *[Chasing the Dream](/F2:_Chasing_the_Dream)*, chronicled the [2019 Formula 2 Championship](/2019_Formula_2_Championship), following the aspirations and struggles of the next generation of potential F1 stars.

The pattern continued, with subsequent second and third seasons of *[Chasing the Dream](/F2:_Chasing_the_Dream)* covering the [2020](/2020_Formula_2_Championship) and [2021](/2021_Formula_2_Championship) F2 Championships, premiering in 2021 and 2022 respectively. By the fourth and fifth seasons, which documented the [2022](/2022_Formula_2_Championship) and [2023 Formula 2 Championships](/2023_Formula_2_Championship), the series expanded its reach, becoming available not only on [F1 TV](/F1_TV) but also free-to-air on [YouTube](/YouTube) during their respective years, further democratizing access to the drama of junior motorsport. This phenomenon, often dubbed the "Drive to Survive train," has seen a multitude of other motorsports series jump on board, with [Formula E](/Formula_E), [NASCAR](/NASCAR), and [IndyCar](/IndyCar) all launching their own respective docuseries, proving that a dose of manufactured drama and behind-the-scenes access is now considered a prerequisite for engaging modern audiences.

